message.content:
 In a JavaScript web app, you can use the FileSystem API (or IndexedDB) to save text to a local file. Here's an example of using the FileSystem API:

1. Check if the browser supports the FileSystem API by checking the `window.webkitStorageInfo` object. If it exists and has a value of 'quotaAvailable', you can proceed with using the FileSystem API.
```javascript
if (typeof window.webkitStorageInfo !== 'undefined' && window.webkitStorageInfo.quotaAvailable > 0) {
    // Proceed with using the FileSystem API
} else {
    console.log('Browser does not support FileSystem API');
}
```
2. Create a new directory to store your file in:
```javascript
window.requestFileSystem(LocalFileSystem.PERSISTENT, 1024 * 1024, function(fs) {
    // Successfully created a new directory
}, errorHandler);
```
3. Create a new text file within the directory:
```javascript
var dirEntry = fs.root;
dirEntry.getFile('myTextFile.txt', {create: true, exclusive: false}, function(fileEntry) {
    // Successfully created a new text file
}, errorHandler);
```
4. Save the text to the newly-created file:
```javascript
function saveTextToFile(text) {
    var fileWriter = new FileWriter('myTextFile.txt', 'w');
    fileWriter.onwrite = function(e) {
        console.log('Text saved successfully!');
    };
    fileWriter.onerror = errorHandler;
    fileWriter.write(text);
}
```
5. Call the `saveTextToFile()` function with your text:
```javascript
saveTextToFile('Hello, world!');
```
This example uses the FileSystem API to create a directory, a text file within that directory, and then saves some text to the newly-created file. Note that this code assumes you have added error handling functions (`errorHandler()`) for any potential issues with creating or writing to files.
